    Examples
</DocsPageSubtitle>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Basic App Shell">
        Use <Code>LayoutHeader</Code>, <Code>LayoutContent</Code>, and <Code>LayoutFooter</Code> for a simple single-column application shell.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Outlined FullWidth>
        <BasicLayoutExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
    <DocsPageSectionSource Code="BasicLayoutExample" />
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Header Above Sidebar">
        <Paragraph>
            Place <Code>LayoutHeader</Code> before a nested <Code>Layout Sider</Code> when the header should span the full page width.
        </Paragraph>
        <Paragraph>
            This pattern is common for products with global search, notifications, and account actions in the header, plus primary navigation in the sidebar.
        </Paragraph>
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Outlined FullWidth>
        <LayoutWithSiderAndTopHeaderExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
    <DocsPageSectionSource Code="LayoutWithSiderAndTopHeaderExample" />
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Sidebar With View Header">
        Put <Code>LayoutHeader</Code> inside the content-side layout when the header belongs to the current view rather than the whole application.
        This works well for dashboards, detail pages, and workspace screens with contextual actions.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Outlined FullWidth>
        <LayoutWithSiderExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
    <DocsPageSectionSource Code="LayoutWithSiderExample" />
</DocsPageSection>

